 {{For|related races|1960 United States elections}}
 The '''1960 United States Senate elections''' coincided with the [[1960 United States presidential election|election]] of [[John F. Kennedy]] as [[President of the United States|president]]. The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] gained one seat at the expense of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]]. The Democrats nonetheless retained a commanding lead in the Senate with 64 seats to 36. As [[Majority Leader of the United States Senate|Majority Leader]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] was elected [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]], [[Mike Mansfield]] became the new Majority Leader.

 == Retirements ==

 === Democratic seats held by Democrats ===
 # [[#Montana|Montana]]: [[James E. Murray]] (D) was replaced by [[Lee Metcalf]] (D)
 # [[#Oregon|Oregon]]: [[Hall S. Lusk]] (D) was replaced by [[Maurine Neuberger]] (D)
 # [[#Rhode Island|Rhode Island]]: [[Theodore F. Green]] (D) was replaced by [[Claiborne Pell]] (D)

 === Democrats replaced by Republicans ===
 # [[#Wyoming|Wyoming]]: [[Joseph C. O'Mahoney]] (D) was replaced by [[Edwin Keith Thomson]] (R).  But Thomson died before the Congress began and was then replaced by a Democratic appointee.

 === Republican seats held by Republicans ===
