 {{Main|1966 United States Senate election in Mississippi}}
 {{See also|List of United States senators from Mississippi}}
-Incumbent [[James Eastland]], who first entered the Senate in 1941, faced the opposition of [[Prentiss Walker]], the first Republican representment since [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,899203,00.html|title=Nation: Choosing Up|date=June 17, 1966|work=Time|access-date=January 6, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=7084|title=Our Campaigns - MS US Senate Race - Nov 08, 1966|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>
-
-Walker, who voted against the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]], ran on the right of Eastland and solely focused on the white vote, accusing him of not being hard enough in opposing integration and being friendly with President Johnson, accusations to which Eastland partisans opposed the fact Walker nominated a black constituent, Marvell Lang, to the [[Air force academy|Air Force Academy]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Danielson|first=Chris|title=Right Turn? The Republican Party and African-American Politics in Post-1965 Mississippi.|url=https://www.academia.edu/2630532|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Nswst5LbIaEC&pg=PA238&lpg=PA238&dq=prentiss+walker+1966#v=onepage&q=prentiss%20walker%201966&f=false|title=The Senator and the Sharecropper: The Freedom Struggles of James O. Eastland and Fannie Lou Hamer|last=Asch|first=Chris Myers|date=February 1, 2011|publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807878057|location=|pages=238–242|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PZ2DDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1843&lpg=PA1843&dq=prentiss+walker+yerger#v=onepage&q=prentiss%20walker%20yerger&f=false|title=Big Jim Eastland: The Godfather of Mississippi|last=Annis|first=J. Lee|date=July 21, 2016|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=9781496806154|language=en}}</ref> He proudly announced he went to a meeting of the Americans for the Preservation of the White Race, a [[Ku Klux Klan]] front, enabling Eastland to proudly announce he was opposed by both the Klan and the [[AFL–CIO|AFL-CIO]].<ref name=":2" />
+Incumbent [[James Eastland]], who first entered the Senate in 1941, faced the opposition of [[Prentiss Walker]], the first Republican representment since [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |date=June 17, 1966 |title=Nation: Choosing Up |language=en-US |work=Time |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,899203,00.html |access-date=January 6, 2018 |issn=0040-781X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Our Campaigns - MS US Senate Race - Nov 08, 1966 |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=7084 |access-date=January 6, 2018 |website=www.ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>
+
+Walker, who voted against the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]], ran on the right of Eastland and solely focused on the white vote, accusing him of not being hard enough in opposing integration and being friendly with President Johnson, accusations to which Eastland partisans opposed the fact Walker nominated a black constituent, Marvell Lang, to the [[Air force academy|Air Force Academy]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Danielson |first=Chris |title=Right Turn? The Republican Party and African-American Politics in Post-1965 Mississippi. |url=https://www.academia.edu/2630532 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Asch |first=Chris Myers |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Nswst5LbIaEC&pg=PA238&lpg=PA238&dq=prentiss+walker+1966#v=onepage&q=prentiss%20walker%201966&f=false |title=The Senator and the Sharecropper: The Freedom Struggles of James O. Eastland and Fannie Lou Hamer |date=February 1, 2011 |publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press |isbn=9780807878057 |pages=238–242 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last=Annis |first=J. Lee |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PZ2DDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1843&lpg=PA1843&dq=prentiss+walker+yerger#v=onepage&q=prentiss%20walker%20yerger&f=false |title=Big Jim Eastland: The Godfather of Mississippi |date=July 21, 2016 |publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi |isbn=9781496806154 |language=en}}</ref> He proudly announced he went to a meeting of the Americans for the Preservation of the White Race, a [[Ku Klux Klan]] front, enabling Eastland to proudly announce he was opposed by both the Klan and the [[AFL–CIO|AFL-CIO]].<ref name=":2" />

 Eastland cast the [[civil rights movement]] with the tar of [[Communism]] and [[Black Power movement|Black Power]] and raised the bloody shirt of Reconstruction against the candidacy of Walker.<ref name=":1" /> He was supported by segregationists [[Thomas Pickens Brady|Tom Brady]], [[George Wallace]] and [[Leander Perez]].<ref name=":2" />

 Most of the White voters stayed with Eastland, and Walker ironically won African-Americans in southwestern Mississippi who wanted to cast a protest vote against Eastland.<ref name=":0" />

-Years later, [[Wirt Yerger]], the chairman of the [[Mississippi Republican Party]] in the 1960s, said that Walker's decision to relinquish his House seat after one term for the vagaries of a Senate race against Eastland was "very devastating" to the growth of the GOP in Mississippi.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V0kTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22very+devastating%22+prentiss+walker&dq=%22very+devastating%22+prentiss+walker|title=The Journal of Mississippi History|last=|first=|date=1985|publisher=Mississippi Department of Archives and History|isbn=|location=|pages=256|language=en}}</ref>
-
-Reverend Clifton Whitley also ran for the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://crdl.usg.edu/people/w/whitley_clifton/|title=Whitley, Clifton|website=crdl.usg.edu|language=en|access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> A [[sore-loser law]] was invoked against Whitley, who ran in the Democratic primary, and he only won one week before the election, thereby preventing to enter any serious campaign or fundraising.<ref name=":2" />
+Years later, [[Wirt Yerger]], the chairman of the [[Mississippi Republican Party]] in the 1960s, said that Walker's decision to relinquish his House seat after one term for the vagaries of a Senate race against Eastland was "very devastating" to the growth of the GOP in Mississippi.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=V0kTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22very+devastating%22+prentiss+walker&dq=%22very+devastating%22+prentiss+walker |title=The Journal of Mississippi History |date=1985 |publisher=Mississippi Department of Archives and History |pages=256 |language=en}}</ref>
+
+Reverend Clifton Whitley also ran for the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Whitley, Clifton |url=http://crdl.usg.edu/people/w/whitley_clifton/ |access-date=January 6, 2018 |website=crdl.usg.edu |language=en}}</ref> A [[sore-loser law]] was invoked against Whitley, who ran in the Democratic primary, and he only won one week before the election, thereby preventing to enter any serious campaign or fundraising.<ref name=":2" />
