 {{Main|1966 United States Senate election in Oregon}}
 {{See also|List of United States senators from Oregon}}
 Incumbent Senator [[Maurine Brown Neuberger]] did not seek re-election. Held during the escalation of United States involvement of the [[Vietnam War]], the race was between [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate and incumbent [[Governor of Oregon]] [[Mark Hatfield]], who opposed the war, and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] congressman [[Robert B. Duncan]], who supported the war. In an unusual move, Oregon's other Senator, Democrat [[Wayne Morse]], who also opposed the war, crossed party lines to endorse Hatfield, who won in a close election, his first of five terms in the United States Senate.

-In March 1960, first-term U.S. senator [[Richard L. Neuberger]] died in office. Despite calls to appoint his widow, [[Maurine Brown Neuberger]], to the position, Governor [[Mark Hatfield]] instead appointed [[Oregon Supreme Court]] justice [[Hall S. Lusk]] to fill the position until a [[1960 United States Senate special election in Oregon|November special election]]. Hatfield stated that he intended to have appointed Neuberger, but that he wanted to appoint someone who would be focused on completing the remaining eight months of the term and not running in the [[1960 United States Senate election in Oregon|regular-term Senate election]] as Neuberger had announced she would.<ref name=nyt031660>{{cite news
- | url        =https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/03/16/99852789.pdf
- | title      =Oregon Justice, Democrat, gets Neuberger's seat in U. S. Senate
- | newspaper  =[[The New York Times]]
- | date       =March 16, 1960
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> Some observers noted that Hatfield, a Republican, though required by state law to appoint someone of the same political party as the late Senator Neuberger, did not want to give the other party the political advantage of incumbency.<ref name=nyt031660/><ref name=wic>{{cite web
- | url        =http://womenincongress.house.gov/member-profiles/profile.html?intID=183#foot8
- | title      =Women in Congress: Maurine B. Neuberger, Senator from Oregon
- | publisher  =United States Congress
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
- | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723034037/http://womenincongress.house.gov/member-profiles/profile.html?intID=183#foot8
- | archive-date=July 23, 2011
- | url-status =dead
-}}</ref>
-
-Neuberger went on to win the special election over former Oregon governor [[Elmo Smith]],<ref name=wic/> but despite the urging of Oregon congressman [[Robert B. Duncan]],<ref name=mapes>{{cite news
- | url        =http://blog.oregonlive.com/mapesonpolitics/2011/04/bob_duncan_and_his_three_losin.html
- | title      =Bob Duncan and his three losing—but history-making—U.S. Senate races
- | last       =Mapes
- | first      =Jeff
- | date       =April 30, 2011
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
- | newspaper  =[[The Oregonian]]
-}}</ref> she chose not to run for a second term in 1966, citing health issues, poor relations with Oregon's senior Senator [[Wayne Morse]], and the burden of fundraising.<ref name=wic/> Duncan also urged fellow Oregon congressperson [[Edith Green]] to run for the post, but Green also declined.<ref name=mapes/>
-
-On the seventh anniversary of his inauguration as Oregon's 29th governor, Hatfield announced his candidacy for the Republican nomination.<ref name=hatfieldseeks>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=06lVAAAAIBAJ&pg=6309%2C2097700
- | title      =Hatfield seeks seat in Senate
- | date       =January 12, 1966
- | newspaper  =[[The Register-Guard]]
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> In his announcement, Hatfield focused on the economic achievements in the state since his election, citing record-high employment and the creation of 138,000 jobs.<ref name=hatfieldannounces>{{cite news
- | url        =https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/01/13/79279209.pdf
- | title      =Hatfield announces his candidacy for the Senate
- | newspaper  =The New York Times
- | date       =January 13, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> Hatfield was considered vulnerable on the subject of the Vietnam War, which he opposed, in contrast with 75% of Oregonians, who favored the war.<ref name=distinction>{{cite news
- | last       =Walth
- | first      =Brent
- | title      =Mark of distinction
- | newspaper  =[[The Oregonian]]
- | date       =December 29, 1996}}
-</ref> Hatfield's views on the war had been strongly affected by his own experiences: as a U.S. Navy ensign in [[World War II]], he had been among the first to walk through the devastation caused by [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|the atomic bombing of Hiroshima]]; in a later assignment in Vietnam, he saw first-hand how imperialism led to incredible disparity, with countless Vietnamese living in poverty next to opulent French mansions.<ref name=distinction/> The war issue gave Hatfield competition from several minor candidates on the right, but Hatfield nonetheless won by a wide margin, besting his nearest competitor, conservative evangelist Walter Huss, by a nearly 6–1 margin.<ref>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wNUzAAAAIBAJ&pg=616,2928300
- | title      =Oregon: one war foe loses, another wins
