-In March 1966, Duncan announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination, which was quickly endorsed by Neuberger.<ref name=abell>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RigRAAAAIBAJ&pg=6083%2C79719
- | title      =Duncan joins Senate race
- | last       =Abell
- | first      =Ron
- | newspaper  =The Register-Guard
- | date       =March 2, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> In his speech announcing his candidacy, Duncan reiterated his strong support for President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s escalation of the Vietnam War with its goal of stopping Communist expansion in Asia.<ref name=abell/> Duncan's strong announcement exposed a rift among Oregon Democrats, including Oregon's senior Senator [[Wayne Morse]], a leading anti-war voice,<ref name=abell/> and Duncan's House colleague, [[Edith Green]]. Green had urged Duncan to run, but Duncan's hawkish statement troubled her.<ref name=duscha>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UnszAAAAIBAJ&pg=2448,2619570
- | title      =Oregon anti-war candidate gains Rep. Green's support
- | last       =Duscha
- | first      =Julius
- | authorlink =Julius Duscha
- | date       =May 24, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
- | newspaper  =[[The Spokesman-Review]]
-}}</ref> Soon after Duncan announced his candidacy, Howard Morgan, a former member of the [[Federal Power Commission]], announced he was running as an anti-war option to Duncan. Morgan had the support of Morse and Green (though Green's endorsement did not come until the final week of the campaign),<ref name=duscha/><ref name=abell2>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PatVAAAAIBAJ&pg=6180,2323355
- | title      =Morgan joins Senate race
- | last       =Abell
- | first      =Ron
- | newspaper  =The Register-Guard
- | date       =March 11, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nhxjAAAAIBAJ&pg=2924,5549980
- | title      =Supporter of Viet war wins Oregon primary
- | newspaper  =The Rochester Sentinel
- | date       =May 25, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> and Duncan had the endorsement of most of the party organization and the major newspapers in the state. When the results were announced, Duncan won by a nearly 2-1 margin in one of the first elections in which the Vietnam War was a central issue.<ref name=davies>{{cite news
- | url        =https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/05/25/82443589.pdf
- | title      =Vietnam critic defeated
- | newspaper  =The New York Times
- | last       =Davies
- | first      =Lawrence E
- | date       =May 25, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref>
-
-{{Election box begin no change| title=Democratic primary for the United States Senate from Oregon, 1966<ref name=66dp>{{cite web
- | url        =http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=497100
- | title      =Oregon US Senate Democratic Primary Race, May 24, 1966
- | publisher  =ourcampaigns.com
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011}}</ref>
+{{End}}
+In March 1966, Duncan announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination, which was quickly endorsed by Neuberger.<ref name="abell">{{Cite news |last=Abell |first=Ron |date=March 2, 1966 |title=Duncan joins Senate race |work=The Register-Guard |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RigRAAAAIBAJ&pg=6083%2C79719 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> In his speech announcing his candidacy, Duncan reiterated his strong support for President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s escalation of the Vietnam War with its goal of stopping Communist expansion in Asia.<ref name=abell/> Duncan's strong announcement exposed a rift among Oregon Democrats, including Oregon's senior Senator [[Wayne Morse]], a leading anti-war voice,<ref name=abell/> and Duncan's House colleague, [[Edith Green]]. Green had urged Duncan to run, but Duncan's hawkish statement troubled her.<ref name="duscha">{{Cite news |last=Duscha |first=Julius |author-link=Julius Duscha |date=May 24, 1966 |title=Oregon anti-war candidate gains Rep. Green's support |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UnszAAAAIBAJ&pg=2448,2619570 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> Soon after Duncan announced his candidacy, Howard Morgan, a former member of the [[Federal Power Commission]], announced he was running as an anti-war option to Duncan. Morgan had the support of Morse and Green (though Green's endorsement did not come until the final week of the campaign),<ref name=duscha/><ref name="abell2">{{Cite news |last=Abell |first=Ron |date=March 11, 1966 |title=Morgan joins Senate race |work=The Register-Guard |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PatVAAAAIBAJ&pg=6180,2323355 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=May 25, 1966 |title=Supporter of Viet war wins Oregon primary |work=The Rochester Sentinel |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nhxjAAAAIBAJ&pg=2924,5549980 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> and Duncan had the endorsement of most of the party organization and the major newspapers in the state. When the results were announced, Duncan won by a nearly 2-1 margin in one of the first elections in which the Vietnam War was a central issue.<ref name="davies">{{Cite news |last=Davies |first=Lawrence E |date=May 25, 1966 |title=Vietnam critic defeated |work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/05/25/82443589.pdf |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref>
