-The general election was now set up between two participants whose views on the Vietnam War were in direct opposition to many in their party: Duncan, a pro-war Democrat and Hatfield, an anti-war Republican.<ref name=mapes/><ref name=balmer>{{cite journal
- | last       =Balmer
- | first      =Donald G.
- | title      =The 1966 Election in Oregon
- | journal    =The Western Political Quarterly
- | volume     =20
- | issue      =2
- | date       =June 1967
- | pages      =593–601
- | jstor      =446088
- | doi        =10.2307/446088
-}}</ref> With more than three-quarters of Oregonians sharing his view on the war, Duncan used the issue to attack Hatfield, stating that the outcome of the war would determine "whether Americans will die in the buffalo grass of Vietnam or the rye grass of Oregon."<ref name=distinction/><ref name=johnson>{{cite book
- | title      =Congress and the Cold War
- | last       =Johnson
- | first      =Robert David
- | publisher  =Cambridge University Press
- | url        =https://books.google.com/books?id=dEYNTXxgcF8C&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q&f=false
- | location   =New York
- | year       =2006
- | isbn       =978-0-521-82133-9
- | page       =134
-}}</ref> Duncan also stressed that his election was necessary to provide a pro-Government voice for Oregon to counteract the anti-war views of Senator Morse.<ref name=johnson/> Morse, who had strongly supported Duncan's rival in the primary, now went across party lines and threw his support to Hatfield, though he did not campaign for him.<ref name=mapes/><ref name=johnson/>
-
-Hatfield, whose popularity as Governor had made him the favorite in the race, soon found his campaign in trouble. Morse's support backfired among many Republicans; Morse had left their party in 1952 to join the Democrats a few years later, and many worried that Hatfield would follow the same path.<ref name=turner>{{cite news
- | url        =https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/11/06/83550873.pdf
- | title      =Hatfield stages Oregon recovery
- | last       =Turner
- | first      =Wallace
- | authorlink =Wallace Turner
- | newspaper  =The New York Times
- | date       =November 6, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref><ref name=evans>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FOBNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7080,396684
- | last       =Evans
- | first      =Rowland
- | authorlink =Rowland Evans
- | author2    =Robert Novak
- | authorlink2=Robert Novak
- | title      =Oregon vote won't be Viet Nam referendum
- | date       =October 5, 1966
- | newspaper  =The Free Lance Star
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> At a June conference of governors of all 50 states, Hatfield was the lone dissenter on a resolution expressing support for the war, calling the resolution a "blank check" for President Johnson's conduct of the war.<ref name=johnson/><ref name=governors>{{cite news
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BOdVAAAAIBAJ&pg=4212%2C1366844
- | title      =Governors back Viet action
- | newspaper  =The Register-Guard
- | date       =July 8, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> By the middle of the summer, fueled by the departure of Republican hawks (such as former [[Oregon State Treasurer]] and 1962 Senate candidate [[Sig Unander]] who wholeheartedly endorsed Duncan), and with a strong majority of voters in the state already registered as Democrats, Duncan surged to a lead in most polls.<ref name=turner/>
-
-While Hatfield did not back away from his war stance, he sought to focus his campaign on other issues, chiefly focusing on the Johnson administration's economic policies that, in Hatfield's view, had created a recession that was creating unemployment in Oregon's timber industry.<ref name=mapes/><ref name=turner/> As the election neared in early fall, Hatfield had pulled even with Duncan with momentum on his side.<ref name=turner/> Hatfield won in 27 of Oregon's 36 counties en route to a solid but narrow 52%-48% victory.<ref name=win>{{cite news
- | title      =Hatfield, McCall win
- | url        =https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=4pF9x-cDGsoC&dat=19661109&printsec=frontpage&hl=en
- | newspaper  =The Register-Guard
- | date       =November 9, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref><ref name=defeats>{{cite news
- | url        =https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/11/09/106221915.pdf
- | title      =Hatfield defeats Duncan in Oregon
- | newspaper  =The New York Times
- | date       =November 9, 1966
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011
-}}</ref> In his victory speech, Hatfield maintained that the vote was not a referendum on the war and that "neither [[Hanoi]] nor [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] should misread the results."<ref name=win/>
-
-{{Election box begin no change| title=[[1966 United States Senate elections|1966 United States Senate election in Oregon]]<ref name=66gen>{{cite web
- | url        =http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=7066
- | title      =Oregon US Senate Race, Nov 8, 1966
- | publisher  =ourcampaigns.com
- | accessdate =June 17, 2011}}</ref>
+{{End}}
+The general election was now set up between two participants whose views on the Vietnam War were in direct opposition to many in their party: Duncan, a pro-war Democrat and Hatfield, an anti-war Republican.<ref name=mapes/><ref name="balmer">{{Cite journal |last=Balmer |first=Donald G. |date=June 1967 |title=The 1966 Election in Oregon |journal=The Western Political Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=593–601 |doi=10.2307/446088 |jstor=446088}}</ref> With more than three-quarters of Oregonians sharing his view on the war, Duncan used the issue to attack Hatfield, stating that the outcome of the war would determine "whether Americans will die in the buffalo grass of Vietnam or the rye grass of Oregon."<ref name=distinction/><ref name="johnson">{{Cite book |last=Johnson |first=Robert David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEYNTXxgcF8C&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Congress and the Cold War |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-521-82133-9 |location=New York |page=134}}</ref> Duncan also stressed that his election was necessary to provide a pro-Government voice for Oregon to counteract the anti-war views of Senator Morse.<ref name=johnson/> Morse, who had strongly supported Duncan's rival in the primary, now went across party lines and threw his support to Hatfield, though he did not campaign for him.<ref name=mapes/><ref name=johnson/>
+
+Hatfield, whose popularity as Governor had made him the favorite in the race, soon found his campaign in trouble. Morse's support backfired among many Republicans; Morse had left their party in 1952 to join the Democrats a few years later, and many worried that Hatfield would follow the same path.<ref name="turner">{{Cite news |last=Turner |first=Wallace |author-link=Wallace Turner |date=November 6, 1966 |title=Hatfield stages Oregon recovery |work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/11/06/83550873.pdf |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name="evans">{{Cite news |last=Evans |first=Rowland |author-link=Rowland Evans |last2=Robert Novak |author-link2=Robert Novak |date=October 5, 1966 |title=Oregon vote won't be Viet Nam referendum |work=The Free Lance Star |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FOBNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7080,396684 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> At a June conference of governors of all 50 states, Hatfield was the lone dissenter on a resolution expressing support for the war, calling the resolution a "blank check" for President Johnson's conduct of the war.<ref name=johnson/><ref name="governors">{{Cite news |date=July 8, 1966 |title=Governors back Viet action |work=The Register-Guard |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BOdVAAAAIBAJ&pg=4212%2C1366844 |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> By the middle of the summer, fueled by the departure of Republican hawks (such as former [[Oregon State Treasurer]] and 1962 Senate candidate [[Sig Unander]] who wholeheartedly endorsed Duncan), and with a strong majority of voters in the state already registered as Democrats, Duncan surged to a lead in most polls.<ref name=turner/>
+
+While Hatfield did not back away from his war stance, he sought to focus his campaign on other issues, chiefly focusing on the Johnson administration's economic policies that, in Hatfield's view, had created a recession that was creating unemployment in Oregon's timber industry.<ref name=mapes/><ref name=turner/> As the election neared in early fall, Hatfield had pulled even with Duncan with momentum on his side.<ref name=turner/> Hatfield won in 27 of Oregon's 36 counties en route to a solid but narrow 52%-48% victory.<ref name="win">{{Cite news |date=November 9, 1966 |title=Hatfield, McCall win |work=The Register-Guard |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=4pF9x-cDGsoC&dat=19661109&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name="defeats">{{Cite news |date=November 9, 1966 |title=Hatfield defeats Duncan in Oregon |work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/11/09/106221915.pdf |access-date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> In his victory speech, Hatfield maintained that the vote was not a referendum on the war and that "neither [[Hanoi]] nor [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] should misread the results."<ref name=win/>
+
+{{Election box begin no change| title=[[1966 United States Senate elections|1966 United States Senate election in Oregon]]<ref name="66gen">{{Cite web |title=Oregon US Senate Race, Nov 8, 1966 |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=7066 |access-date=June 17, 2011 |publisher=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>
 }}
