 {{Main|1966 United States Senate special election in South Carolina}}
 The election resulted from the death of Senator [[Olin D. Johnston]] in 1965. Then-[[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] [[Donald S. Russell]] entered in a prearranged agreement with [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Robert Evander McNair]] in which Russell would resign his post so that he could be appointed Senator. However, former Governor [[Ernest Hollings|Fritz Hollings]] won the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[primary election]] and went on to beat [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]] [[Marshall Parker]] in the general election to fill the remaining two years of the unexpired term.

 In the [[1962 South Carolina gubernatorial election|1962 gubernatorial election]], [[Donald S. Russell]] had stated that he would he serve out a full term and not seek a higher office. However, midway through his term he resigned from the governorship so that he could be appointed to the [[United States Senate]]. Russell faced a challenge in the Democratic primary from former Governor [[Ernest Hollings|Fritz Hollings]], who had lost to [[Olin D. Johnston]] in the [[1962 United States Senate election in South Carolina|1962 primary]] for the same Senate seat. On June 14, the [[South Carolina Democratic Party]] held their primary election and Hollings scored a comfortable victory over Russell to become the Democratic nominee.

