@@ -13,25 +13,26 @@
 To reduce the amount of time required to fill electoral vacancies, in [[special elections]] Texas dispenses with [[party primary|party primaries]] and instead uses a [[jungle primary]] system. Candidates of all parties (or no party) appear on the same ballot; if no single one of them receives 50-percent plus 1 vote, the two highest vote-getters advance to a [[run-off election|runoff]] irrespective of party affiliation. Most famously, in [[William A. Blakley#Senate appointment and subsequent loss|Texas' special election of 1961]] [[John Tower]], a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], was able to win a [[United States Senate]] seat in [[Solid South|then-overwhelmingly Democratic]] Texas.  

